column1: 89	w7VSMULJ9GtRi3CBRxoJtg	2013-10-24	oZ7CJI3Mwem_KVJ8Ds30BQ	1	"It is really hard for me to review Wholey's in one post because I am not sure what the store is trying to be.  Is it a modern fish market? Is it a grocery store?  I would just like Wholey's to choose an identity and strive to be great at it.

I was always taught that a good fish market shouldn't smell fishy. Too many times Wholey's smells like the inside of my tackle box. The fish selection at Wholey's is greater than your normal supermarket but not what I would expect from a top notch fish market. I am not a big fan of all of their processed frozen fish product.  Also the the quality to price ratio seems to be a little off.  With that said there are deals to be had if you pay attention.  My other issue is with Wholey's as a full service fish monger.  Every time I have had a question about a type of fish the staff had seemed pretty ignorant.  I would put them at the level of a giant eagle employee but lower than the monger at Whole Foods.  I also  take issue with Wholey's charging for scaling or even taking the fins and tail off of a fish.  This has been complimentary at any real fish monger that I have ever been to.
This weekend I purchased 2 pounds of the ocean perch filets that were on sale thinking that they would be a quick ingredient for a dinner party that I was hosting. Today
column2: when I went to pull them out
column3: I found to my dismay
column4: that they were poorly butchered.  Every filet had large portions that had not been scaled completely and the filets had bones (not pin bones) hanging off the bottom. This added over an hour to my prep time and left me quite unsatisfied. If I had wanted to take the time to break a fish down I would have purchased whole fish from the start.  Needless to say I expected more from one of Pittsburgh's premier fish mongers. I also emailed Wholey's and have still not received a response.

column1: Will I go back? Probably. But only because they are the only place that I can pork belly that is not frozen  Just be aware that there are better fish mongers in Pittsburgh and even in the Strip."	review	-6rEfobYjMxpUWLNxszaxQ	{u'funny': 0

I mixed mine as I love horseradish but my friend would have preferred it on the side or in another bowl as he isn't a fan.  The shrimp were big and fresh and delicious.  I mean- can you really mess up cold shrimp...?  The calamari took over a half hour to arrive.  It was pleasing to the eye and smelled delicious.  It had grilled onions & peppers on it with a slight spice dusted on top.  I thought it was delicious but my wife wasn't digging it.  She thought it was overcooked & rubbery. column1: 130	A3ryEM41LVJ8WPTQLDzbHg	2014-10-31	fuIEEqvDJOs9wHH46zdsNg	5	"FREE CIGARS?  Yep- keep reading... but...
Don't go here...!

If you don't like smoke- don't go here.  If you have OCD and get hives when you see dust- don't go here.  If you don't like friendly old guys reliving their youth- don't go here.  If you're afraid of parallel parking- don't go here.  If you are allergic to vinyl seating surfaces- don't go here.  If you can't stand mellow classic rock (read: Led Zepplin)- don't go here.  If you're in a hurry- don't go here.  If you request 'Non-Smoking' ALL the time- don't go here.  If you are trying to become a hipster by smoking cigars- don't come here.
Have I made my point?  But you're still reading...?  Great
column2: then read on...

column1: If you enjoy a good smoke
column2: if you have a few hours to kill
column3: if you love the idea of smoking in your own living room but hate the 'sticky-dirt' that accumulates on the walls only to be evident when you move your pictures around and find that your walls are 3 shades darker than when you first painted them
column4: if you enjoy hearing stories that start out- 'When I was younger...' or 'When I was your age...'
column5: if you're not allergic to dust
column6: if you have an open mind... you get the idea.  This place is a gem.

column1: I'm a chill
column2: relaxed
column3: open minded
column7: love to BYO (as you can carry a 6 pack in here) kind of guy.  I was brought up in a 2 smoker household
column8: my father quit cold turkey when I was about 12
column9: my mother has reduced her cigarette intake drastically but still smokes daily.  I turned out ok.  No lasting effects
column10: no long term issues.  I can't recall when I tried my first cigar and I can admit- I wasn't hooked.  I have evolved over time.  Now when I want to relax

column1: Cigar Camp happens every Saturday.  What's that
column2: you ask?  It's kind of like WDVE's Electric Lunch.  Michelle Michaels asks for 'lunch requests'
column3: she promises to 'try to get it on...' she 'Cooks it up & serves it hot'... but there's no lunch.  Here at Blooms- there's no Camp.  There's no tents
column5: no smores...  What there is is a very friendly owner (Mark) holding court and acting like the moderator of the debate on life.  My wife learned about Furries here
column6: for god's sake!  She thought I was pulling her leg when I tried to explain it but after our second visit to Blooms when the old guys were discussing the upcoming weekend
column7: she learned all she needed to know.  Cigar Camp does feed you though- there's usually ribs
column12: all supplied by Mark (with a required purchase of course.  We all know there's No Free Lunch).  The 'campers' also bring stuff and we had our first taste of home-made Lemoncello here.

column1: Our first visit we learned how to get free cigars.  Years ago there was a bar in Homestead named Chiodos.  Chiodos was decorated with eclectic stuff.  Eclectic stuff and Bra's...  TONS of Bra's...  Well
column2: I'm not sure who 'came' first- Blooms or Chiodos but Mark has bras all over the ceiling of the humidor.  I guess it keeps the cigars happy.  Anyway- we were taking the tour and my wife asked about them.  Turns out- if you give him your bra- you get a free cigar.  If you take it off in front of the 'cigar smoking court'- you get 2 cigars.  If you let him take a polaroid- 3 cigars.  My loving and open minded wife earned me 2 free cigars.  Pictures don't lie- but reviews can
column3: she said.  ;)

column1: As for prices and the review that says the prices are high... Are you HIGH...?  Mark will take you to the $2 bin and tell you that this cigar is better than the $14 one 2 shelves over.  He'll tell you that the $4 ones are only half as good as the $8 ones.  He's not trying to win you over- he's telling you to think for yourself.  We're all individuals with our own tastes.  Try the $2 ones first
column2: if you don't like them try a different one.  There's that saying that says 'You eat with your eyes first...' and those $2 cigars don't look like much but they have every bit as much taste as a $10 one with a fancy band.  Tell Mark what you want to spend and he'll pick the best cigar for your needs...

column1: Where am I gong with this review...?  I'm not exactly sure.  It's my very own 'trip down memory lane' that's continuously being added to
column2: I guess.  But in the infamous words of Jimmy Buffett- 'The best navigators are not quite sure where they're going until they get there...'

column1: Thank you
column2: good night and don't forget to tip your bartenders...  :D"	review	Qs5dcst13DnQJwaBcR4VGg	{u'funny': 1
column3: u'useful': 1

column2: and the local media certainly doesn't help much for the local arts) and saw that they were presenting 'August: Osage County'...and that the tickets were $24. So we decided to give them a try.

column1: And we're damned glad that we did. This was a top notch VERY high production value presentation
column2: of a superbly written and award laden script.

column1: The casting was local
column2: and the cream of the crop of local actors. The set was beautiful and functional
column3: and the direction gave the play the exact spark and airborn sizzle that live theater often misses out on in Pittsburgh. This was a three act LONG play that didn't have us nodding off after 40 minutes...which I can NOT say for the 90 minute no-intermission plays that I've seen at the Public.

column1: I will also say that the local casting wasn't just a list of 'Equity' professionals
column2: with a few Point Park or CMU students as low-budget 'filler'. Every role on that stage was performed by someone who knew what they were doing
column3: and they all did it perfectly well.

column1: As I mentioned
column2: hard to base an entire body of work on seeing one play - but if this one play is an accurate representation
column3: then this is a theater to get on their e-mail list - and with their affordable ticket prices
column4: it's not so 'scary' to take a chance on their productions.

column1: The only downfall is the location
column2: which has been pretty much forgotten by the Pittsburgh 'development' geniuses
column3: except of course for UPMC
column4: which has surrounded the one time 'arts' block with behemoth medical facilities. There is limited parking nearby
column5: and there is absolutely nothing to eat within walking distance. Not so problematic if you have a car
column6: but not so easy to plan anything else if you rely on public transportation
column8: the Access vans for the disabled. They do have a cafe of sorts
column9: but it's pretty much a generic Starbuck's without the Starbuck's.

column1: The theater is ancient. I was there two hundred years ago as a child
column2: and it really looks at though nothing has been changed in the auditorium (except of course the name
column3: which now bears the name of the most recent wealthy donor) since I was there in fourth grade. But that's what an old theater SHOULD be. For me
column6: it's about the quality of what I'm watching AND paying for.

column1: This was a locally produced play worth paying for
column2: a rarity in da burgh. And we look forward to exploring further!"	review	tAKjY3bQXH51msJbOHYPmQ	{u'funny': 3
column3: u'useful': 6

column1: 187	QGWyhvvLjaT1Szw-segoOg	2012-09-22	ElunFODXY2lwcQiGdzZ2dg	2	"So
column2: the Eat N Park company decided to renovate the Squirrel Hill shop.  They spend hundreds of thousands of dollars to make the place look hip and trendy
column3: with high tables and chairs
column4: garage door windows to allow for opening and closing during the nicer seasons to 'open air' the place. They spent money on new art that shows the neighborhood. The gave the facade a facelift with stone and paint

column1: Everything is new. New counters and display cases
column2: new carpeting
column3: regular chairs and tables
column4: and upholstered booths. New lighting fixtures. There's even a TV for - well - yet MORE sports coverage in da burgh.

column1: On the wall between the restrooms is a huge banner boasting of how much money they've given to local charities annually. If I recall correctly

column4: and whatever this new bistroid is that's next to the old but new Eat N Park. They have money to renovate the Eat N Park into an apparent trendy high end diner. They have enough money to donate $2 Million to charity.

column1: But dear Eat N Park...what about the FOOD?
Generally
column2: the only reason my friend and I go to Eat N Park is to grab the breakfast buffet before an afternoon of movies.  Which we did this morning
column3: and what did we find?

column1: A big fancy renovation - with the same ol' crappy food.

Scrambled eggs out of a carton that would make a World War II military man feel right at home. Rubbery pancakes. The same out-of-a-can cheese sauce for whatever you wanted to ladle it over. The same flavorless sausage gravy for dried out biscuits. Sausage greasy enough to lube your 1957 Buick. And they can't even be bothered with the little potato pancakes that used to actually be kind of yummy. One the first trip to the buffet
column2: they had maybe six potato-pancake-like chunks left in the pan
column3: and when we came back for more

column1: I found humor in the fact that they now try to sell their own bags of coffee along with the smiley cookies in the dessert counter
column2: when the coffee that comes to the table is pretty much brown water
column3: that my friend and I refer to as 'tea-fee'.

column1: Eat N Park is (correct me if I'm wrong) SUPPOSED to be a 'restaurant'.  And in my opinion
column2: a restaurant should be know for its...well...FOOD.

column1: Now I have learned
column2: especially as decades passed and corners were cut for profits (which they are apparently making
column3: considering the new bistroids
column5: and the charity work) NOT to expect much in the way of 'food' from an Eat N Park. They didn't nick-name it 'Eat N Puke' for nothing.

column1: However
column2: like most corporate entities in our country today...if you're going to show off and brag about your 'profits'
column3: it had BETTER be reflected in your product!

column1: You may have given the visuals a stunning make-over. And yeah
column2: it's pretty. However
column3: in the rejuvenation of your brand and your product

column1: Because in the end (literally) it's the same garbage you've been passing off as 'food' for the last twenty years. The only thing the facelift has inspired is perhaps the change of the apt nick-name...from Eat N Puke...to maybe 'Masticate N Regurgitate'.

column2: mix in some milk and whip them to make scrambled eggs? It's too expensive to throw potatoes in a food processor with some eggs
column3: flour and seasonings to make your own potato pancakes?

column1: But we can afford a real stone facade

column1: 190	RhOTBt7ISr2rhXisSMLTSw	2011-12-15	_oojsrSbwM5aQR6y9BwFrg	5	"I discovered Spice Island shortly after they'd opened in the 90's

column1: 191	Q4ULAiIE2qCA4RYplCTrUQ	2011-11-29	b6vhZB1bT-3bSWnw_Z5W0A	2	"Once upon a time...before profiteering became more important than product
column2: there were a lot of good food items to be had.   Anyone remember when Twinkies or Ho Ho's actually tasted like food
column3: and not like chemical compounds?

column1: Well
column2: the same applies to Primanti Brothers.

column1: Once upon a time
column2: there was a little sandwich shop in Pittsburgh that was trying very hard to be like the famous steak sandwich shops in Philly.  After all
column3: Pittsburgh really wasn't (and still isn't) 'known' for anything other than dirty steel mills
column4: followed closely by closed steel mills
column5: and the mill workers who sat around waiting for them to reopen
column6: even after they'd been torn down and the property turned into malls.

column1: Primanti Brother at one time was a decent sandwich shop with a quirky gimmick.  They put your sides ON the sandwich.  Yes
column2: you could get a steak sandwich piled high with your favorites...french fries and cole slaw...in addition to the usual lettuce
column3: tomatoes

column1: As time rolled by
column2: the restaurants sprang up in several locations around the city
column3: primarily anywhere that there might be a mall nearby
column4: or a bunch of drunks who really didn't care WHAT they were eating
column5: and there even sprang up one of the shops in Ft. Lauderdale.

column1: As the business grew
column2: the Primanti Brothers started cutting corners to maximize profits.  The meat became nothing more than Steak-Ums
column3: and they started adding everything under the sun that could be served on a bun to their menu to try to draw in more people.  A nice healthy chicken breast...grilled in the same grease as everything else and topped with fries and cole slaw.

column1: Now
column2: anyone not from Pittsburgh should know...native Pittsburghers are not exactly known for having distinguished tastes...in anything.  In fact
column3: people in Pittsburgh will stand and give a raving standing ovation and scream 'faaaaabulous'...for what most folks around the country in more metropolitan cities would say 'eh'.

column1: Last year
column2: I had jury duty.  The Pittsburgh Courthouse is located near one of the many Primanti grease pits.  I thought I'd try a fish sandwich since I was on a limited budget for the day
column3: and time was too short to sit down in any other restaurant.

column1: Greasy
column2: didn't taste much like fish
column3: the batter was soggy from the grease
column4: the cheese clearly came in little squares from a plastic package
column5: and even the tartar sauce couldn't make it more palatable.  My stomach felt rock laden the rest of the day.

column1: More recently
column2: a couple from San Francisco came into the store where I work
column3: which is near one of the Primanti restaurants.  They'd heard all the hype

column1: The woman said to me: ""WHAT is up with Primanti?  Everyone kept telling us we had to have a Primanti while we were in Pittsburgh!""
She looked at me
column2: rolled her eyes
column3: stuck out her tongue and said:  ""Bleeech!""

column1: I shrugged my shoulders and told her I agreed.
I guess we could say that Primanti is kind of the White Castle of Pittsburgh

column1: 211	mVHrayjG3uZ_RLHkLj-AMg	2015-11-06	e11K8g-0m66gDeRz3TgSIQ	5	"I had a hankering for some fried fish tonight and the fish fry at Maximilian Kolbe was going to close before I got home on the bus
column2: and I suggested to my wife and 12 year-old daughter that we try Emil's lounge as WQED's Rick Seback loved the place as did Andrew Zimmern when he visited for the Bizarre Foods America episode featuring Pittsburgh.

column1: The place is in Rankin - a rough around the edges town in the Mon Valley between Swissvale and Braddock.  Don't be put off at first - the outside doesn't have much decoration to speak of and looks like the sort of place that you might think twice about it.  A TGI Fridays it isn't... And thank god for that.
The place is well-kept but a little dated -  no fripperies here.  But we're not here for the Decor - we're here for some dinner.

The menu is basic with reasonable prices.  The meats and seafood are high quality and everything is made to order.  Their stuffed cabbage is regarded as the best in  Pittsburgh.  I love stuffed cabbage but I just made a batch a couple of weeks ago and I'm cabbaged out.  Their Ruebens are   also killer (our waitress raved about them).  My wife and I both settled on fish sandwiches.  These are true Pittsburgh fish Sammiches - fresh fried fish in crispy breading
column2: crammed between enormous pillows of soft
column3: yet chewy and crispy Mancini's Italian bread.  No adornments - just a boatload of hot crispy fish.  Emil's uses thick cod fillets piled high rather than a thin fillet that needs to be broken up to fit in the bun.  Truly a great sandwich.  My daughter had the BLT - looked good and on good bread and they weren't skimpy with the bacon.

column1: The service was very pleasant and friendly and the crowd was a great group of folks.  We all had fun with 4 other tables when my wife pulled up a Trivial Pursuit game on her iPhone and pretty much everyone joined in and had a good laugh.
Overall
column2: if you consider yourself a true Pittsburgher - you must visit this place.  It's one of the few places (Big Jim's in the Run is another) where the spirit of Pittsburgh is alive and hungry.  Please go."	review	k0a-uii8yr__Rl-9ipl_RA	{u'funny': 0

column1: I plan to bring a nice primitivo

column1: The menu is very interesting.  It's a composite of tried-and-tested simplicity and creative genius for the more adventurous.  The dishes are very accurately described

column1: The atmosphere of the place is SO VERY throwback.  It feels like New York City in the 60s or early 70s.  Honestly

column4: in a fond memories of my Italian grandmother kind of way

column6: and if you don't come early
column7: you ARE going to wait.  Good things are worth waiting for
column8: but my advice is to COME EARLY before they get slammed.  By the way
column9: there's a REASON they get slammed
column10: and it's NOT the decor or the view.

column1: I was very surprised to see any negative reviews of this place
column2: and I have a few tips for you:

column1: 1. Don't trust a review of Italian food by someone who doesn't know how to spell ""lasagna.""  The lasagna at La Tavola is excellent
column2: but some people are used to Stouffer's
column3: and their opinions don't count.

column1: 2. Don't trust reviews from impatient reviewers who were unhappy with their experience because they had to wait too long for the food.  There's a REASON you had to wait too long.  People love this place
column2: and they come back often
column3: and sometimes really good food takes time to prepare
column4: unlike the microwave crap that you are accustomed to.  By the way
column5: REAL Italian families can spend HOURS at the dinner table when they gather.

column1: 3. Don't trust reviewers who complain about getting ""too much food"" at an Italian restaurant.  Skinny jeans people have no place at a real Italian table
column2: unless they don't mind finishing their meal over the course of several days
column3: which apparently SOME people have a problem with.

column1: 4. Don't trust reviews by people who claim to be Italians that expect EVERY dish to be over-garliced
column2: over-spiced
column3: and over-priced.  If they don't understand the SUBTLETIES of real Italian cooking
column4: then they probably don't cook for themselves and have been duped by the HIPSTER purveyors of pseudo-Italian bastardizations.  If you want AUTHENTIC
column5: then don't complain when AUTHENTIC doesn't tickle your burned out palate.

column1: 5. Don't trust reviews of Italian food that are written by people who live in places like Utah
column2: and who complain about the food being ""blah"" or claim that they could have made it cheaper themselves at home.  Really?  Subtlety in Italian cooking is authentic.  Simplicity in Italian cooking is authentic.

column1: Rant concluded.  Now
column2: if you want me to repeat this in my NEW YORK ITALIAN kind of way

column1: 274	q_BKmbdlYfQJroJVHfYMUQ	2012-12-11	EXBKIiU-57iTgZ6bzlsiMw	5	"I was out and about on a Saturday afternoon with a good friend and we were in the north side area and he suggested that we eat at ""Legends of the North Side"" since he heard it was good.  We walked into the door and there was a woman standing near the door and she shot us a look of surprise (or frustration) and asked if we had a reservation? Well that wasn't the greeting I was expecting and was surprised at this question since the place was empty but within a half hour I totally understood why.

This small but quaint restaurant filled up very fast.  This establishment is just lovely and was clean and was decorated for the holiday season.  It was cozy.   The menu was small but had something for everyone and the prices weren't too bad but It might be a little pricey if you are on a budget but it's worth it trust me.
The service was excellent.. we received beverages and bread within a moments time.  Our bread basket never remained empty either.
We ordered the ""beans and greens"" as an appetizer and it was delicious. My Italian Mother makes this dish all the time and it was ""almost"" as good as hers - which is saying a lot.
I had penne pasta with sausage
column2: roasted red peppers
column3: olives and artichokes.   It was very tasty but was a bit salty for my taste (think it was the olives) but still delicious.  My friend ordered the Walleye and was very pleased.  The tossed salad that came with my entree was just the right size and everything was fresh.

column1: Fresh greens and was accompanied by carrots
column2: red onions
column3: feta
column4: cherry tomatoes and olives.   By the time we were ready to leave there wasn't an empty table in the place.

column1: The restaurant is located on the corner at a very convenient location in North side with parking available on the street right outside the restaurant. Getting back on 279 was a snitch.
The restroom doors were so festive and unique that I couldn't resist taking a picture !!   The restrooms were also clean too.
I love restaurants that aren't ""chains"" and have their own flair .. and this establishment has that!
I am very happy we decided to have dinner at Legends of the North Shore and will no doubt be visiting again ...
Bravo !"	review	Sjb5e5-gKoLXueFDMc2R8Q	{u'funny': 1

column1: 283	-OwiexFSLiORN7atLezyPw	2015-09-28	l159GcDxCFQDRowwJzFkBg	5	"I grew up eating Mancinis bread and still is a part of my lifestyle.   Every Sunday spaghetti dinner - Mancinis ""twist"" was a staple.  In fact it was un-heard of ""not"" to have the bread at the table.

I remember when I was a little girl spending the holidays at my grandparent's house..my cousins would tear apart the bread (instead of slicing) and dip into butter and garlic and then bake.   I still make that type of garlic bread from time to time and oh that taste just brings me back to my childhood.    So dam good.
My current favorite ...a few slices of twist to accompany ""sponge"" stew (recipe passed from my Italian aunts).
I stop at the bakery probably once or twice a week for bambini pizza shells
column2: breadcrumbs
column3: twist or pepperoni roll.   The bambini's are the perfect size for a personal pizza.  They bake just right on a medium temp in the toaster oven and are just delicious.   I like to draw some lines with a fork and add a little olive oil and seasonings.  The bakery also sells breadcrumbs (un-seasoned) which are handy to have.  I buy the breadcrumbs and keep them in the fridge/freezer and they are fantastic to cook with. I enhance with Italian seasonings right before breading.  The pepperoni rolls are very popular .. and go very fast.  I like to stock up on the hoagie rolls and cut into pieces and freeze.   It's so delightfully convenient that Giant Eagle and Ricci Sausage - amount other establishments carry the bread too.Sure I pick up from time to time .. but the extra few minutes it would take to drive to the bakery is worth it.

column1: I couldn't imagine living in Pittsburgh ""without"" Mancinis bread. It is really the best bread in the world."	review	Sjb5e5-gKoLXueFDMc2R8Q	{u'funny': 0
column2: u'useful': 1

column1: 284	TRLMm_deLvlPNmGNqRxcow	2012-12-18	4LZ1CdxnbLFptkQAy-5NUw	3	"Andy Warhol Museum is a must see attraction in Pittsburgh!
I feel very fortunate to live in Pittsburgh and have access to this great museum.
$20.00 admission may seem a bit high but if you think about it - it's worth it to support the arts.
You can visit the first floor and gift shop for free and you are permitted to take photographs on the first floor too.

There is so much to see at this 7 floor museum.  You could spend an entire day and still not experience everything this museum has to offer.  The store in the museum has so many little unique items that you wouldn't find anywhere else.. from books to cool iphone covers for your phone ..  a lot of interesting little treasures...
The Warhol Caf located on the ground level has coffee
column2: salads .. and comfortable tables and chairs to relax.

column1: There is small parking lot for the museum ($7.00) but it fills up fast.  Theres also parking available on the street.

column1: The secret to shopping at Whole Foods?   BUY WHAT YOU NEED TO EAT THAT DAY.  It's not smart to bulk shop organic produce

column1: 447	3ZVKmuK2l7uXPE6lXY4Dbg	2014-08-06	nkquD2FJgZvyj3bcobqlrg	2	"I will start by saying we have a nice new deck. That is where the good part ends.
Why two stars if we have a nice deck now? Well
column2: it all started in May when we had a man named Al come out and talk to us about the process. He was a true salesman
column3: I'll tell you that. Not a straight shooter
column4: but an excited salesman that wanted to sell... And we bought into it.

column1: He told us they were backed up with the harsh winter and a lot of jobs
column2: but they could probably start by June 24th. Mind you
column3: this was the end of May we met with him. He said they would have to do a survey of our land and get a permit from Dormont before they started. We felt confident in going with them

column1: Here's where things fell apart. Weeks went by with no word from them on the process. Finally I called and left messages. Al finally got in touch with me and the conversation was utterly confusing. He must have not understood me because he just kept talking in circles. So I hung up not knowing what was going on. Finally I called back and the admin told me that the survey could take a couple weeks to come back. I wish Al would have told us that.
So our June 24th date came and went. We finally got our survey. And they were quick to bill us for it
column2: but no word on where we were in the process. I called back a couple times with no real answers from the admin. Apparently they were now waiting for the permit from Dormont.

column1: A month later
column2: I was frustrated and asked to speak with someone at the company. I spoke with someone who told me that Dormont usually takes a week to process the permit
column3: but we were now going on a month. He told me he would bug the guy about it and we finally got it.

column1: I completely understand that waiting on the permit is not their fault
column2: but why no communication about it? Just call me and tell me they're waiting for the permit
column3: but they'll work towards asking Dormont what the hold up is. Seems simple.

column1: Finally we get the permit and work is supposed to start. Tuesday comes and they have to wait for approval from Dormont on holes they're digging. So holes are dug and equipment is put in my backyard and then nothing happens for two days. Where did everyone go? Who knows
column2: because I wasn't informed!

column1: I was upset and contacted the company owner
column2: Dave
column3: by email. I told him how frustrated I was about the lack of communication. He wrote me two sentences that  said ""there will be acres there tomorrow morning to finish and most will be done tomorrow."" Well

column1: Then two other dudes show up two days later and did work for about three hours and left. The main guy comes back the next day and says they did it wrong. So apparently the part about how they wouldn't need access to my house changes to they're drilling bolts into my house to secure he deck.
Finally
column2: the second week into construction
column3: my tiny 10x11 foot deck is done. It was upsetting that they left the deck dirty
column4: and all the dirt and cement they moved around wasn't cleaned up. I even asked them to fill all the holes they dug up and didn't use
column5: and they only filled up one. When you create a construction project
column6: isn't it just good business to clean it up and make it look nice? Didn't happen here.

column1: My main point is
column2: contractors have a reputation for not being the most trustworthy. Why be that company? Why not be an upstanding company that consumers can trust? My main issues with them were that things were not communicated to me properly up front
column3: nor was the ongoing process communicated to me. Then they left everything unfinished in my eyes
column4: leaving the site dirty. I understand things happen and things get delayed
column5: but just email or call me. It's not that hard to keep me updated
column6: it is 2014 with a million ways to be contacted.

column1: Even though I have a nice deck (after I clean things up myself!)
column2: I would not recommend them to anyone."	review	nEYPahVwXGD2Pjvgkm7QqQ	{u'funny': 0

column1: 458	VkFDer80GOrelWALdgNReg	2011-01-17	P5ydJhKAjhhNYDl9yTBMLg	5	"I'm a crazy cat lady and proud of it!

Being a volunteer here has been so fulfilling on many different levels.  It has made me feel so good to be able to help out with something that I feel passionately about.  You can tell that the staff puts a lot of effort into taking care of these animals they accept in.  A lot of times people will say
column2: oh I can't do it
column3: it's too sad.  But the thing is
column4: it's not.  It's actually so great because these animals come here and find loving homes instead of being on the street or in an environment that's toxic.  I rarely see animals there for a long time.  I think that's a testament to the way they are treated while they're in the facility.

column1: Now I'll admit
column2: I'm not the biggest dog fan
column3: so I help out in the cat shelter.  I can talk about that with a lot more knowledge than the dog side.  They just built a new cat facility on their property so they have their own shelter.  The cats are all set up in a huge room.  They have two rooms for people to play with the cats when they are looking to adopt them.  These rooms are also used for ""cat cuddling.""  That's what I do when I volunteer.  I get to take the cats out so that they can play
column4: be cuddled or just run around.  Then the cats are able to get out of the cages and get used to human contact.

column1: The other great thing about the ARL is that they have foster parents who take in cats and dogs while they're waiting to be adopted.  This way
column2: they get a great home environment and it relieves the facility of having too many animals at one time. At different points in the year the adoption rates are different depending on the amount of animals they have.  Cat rates are usually cheaper in the Spring/Summer because there's more coming in and dog rates are cheap in the late summer months.  The added bonus of adopting a pet from the ARL is that they are spade or neutered when you adopt them.  It's actually cheaper then taking them to a normal vet on your own.

column1: I would STRONGLY recommend coming here to check out the animals and hopefully find your next furry friend!  OR you can volunteer!  They have volunteer informational sessions the first Saturday of every month.  After that you only have one training session to complete and you're ready to volunteer!
Just check it out if you're curious.  You won't regret it!  Your new furry friends will appreciate it as well!"	review	nEYPahVwXGD2Pjvgkm7QqQ	{u'funny': 3

We had a very difficult time parking but managed to secure a spot on the street. After ""feeding the meter"" we went to the diner and learned that today and tomorrow they had free street parking due to July 4th holiday.

We laughed it off and were seated fairly promptly. The place is small and very crowded. Food is all homemade from scratch. My girlfriend opted for breakfast so she settled for a veggie omelet with toast and I chose a turkey Rachel. The sandwich came on marble bread and was filled with sauerkraut an cheese. It also came with potato pancakes. Portion sizes were generous and the food was very good.

They are noted for their pancakes which we will try on another visit. We got our meals rather quickly and our waitress was very attentive to our needs. column1: 749	hHUxynhRliO0rdjgPYesOw	2015-10-18	83NATSMBp0hgNw00YgnVVA	5	"The Public theater also known as the O'Reilly theater is a smaller theater used mostly for plays but each year they throw in one musical in their series.

Seating is half moon shaped so people sitting on the side can catch the ""action"" from a different point of view. There are two small balconies surrounding the theater. This theater is very strict regarding use of cell phones inside and we were advised that if anyone took a picture of the set to delete it immediately.

I came to see ""The Diary of Anne Frank"". This is the actual Broadway production that won a Tony back in the 1950s and is based off the writings of the diary itself. I had only seen the movie many years ago but never seen it performed live.
From the tearjerking beginning where Otto Frank is given Anne's diary from Miep Giles
column2: the audience is transported back to 1942 where we meet both the Frank family and their close friends the Van Daan's. Remy Zaken plays the young spirited Anne Frank who despises her mother
column3: greatly attached to her father
column4: and runs in to conflict with the Van Daan's son Peter(excellently portrayed by David Edward Jackson).

column1: The set replicates the tight quarters they had to share as well as the lack of food from rationing tickets. Every night they had variations of beans for dinner. Enter Daniel Krell as Mr. Dussell
column2: a dentist who increases the party in hiding to 8 and is forced to share a room with Anne.

column1: The conflicts with Anne and Mr. Dussell heighten as they each want time to themselves in the room. Amidst the fear of being found out Anne brings a positive spirit which is both quoted in the play from her dairy and at the end.
Anne writes ""In spite of everything
column2: I still believe people are good at heart."" We are drawn to her warmth when near the close of Act 1 she gives home made Hanukkah gifts to everyone in the annex.

column1: Act 2 finds Anne having gone through puberty and beginning to establish a fondness for Peter whom she was on the outs with earlier. Hope for a quick end of the war comes with Miep's announcement of D-Day but is quickly dashed when on Aug 4th
column2: 1944 the annex is raided. The audience does not see the action but throughout the production background noises suggest an air raid
column3: a thief entry
column4: as well as the Gestapo breaking up the house in search of the families.

column1: We are brought back to the beginning of the story where we learn Anne's fate. Only the father survived but the diary served as a legacy for generations to come of one of the best literary works of the Holocaust.

I had a great seat near the front so I felt like I was in the heart of the action. This production was one of the best I had ever seen and truly brought tears to my eyes. I highly recommend this show and am looking forward to future productions there."	review	9HCfCmd0t5GErgm7He6AeQ	{u'funny': 0
column2: u'useful': 0
column3: u'cool': 2}	3.57	{u'profile': 1

column1: 751	XY3sN_2uusMSU9i1WINFeg	2014-12-10	EBSzlpDBLj_bPRNr59LTLQ	4	"The Benedum Center is home to some of the finest productions currently on tour. I've seen some of these musicals on the Broadway series in the cramped Broadway theaters themselves so it is refreshing to be able to see that same show from a larger venue.

It is true that if you have seats to the far right or left then you will miss both the scenery and what happens on that side of the stage but that is true with most any theater. I find that if I am unable to get good seats and must sit far away or in the balcony then I bring some ""opera"" glasses to help me get a close up of the stars and the action.
In addition to musical theater the Benedum Center offers special performances like the Nutcracker or special singers or groups depending upon the time of the year.
Normally the CLO now has this new gimmick going on where they will take a picture of you for free in front of a show marquee and then post it on Facebook so you can download the image.
It does have handicapped accessible access as well as free listening devices for the hearing impaired.

They do have narrow areas for gift shopping as well as for purchasing beverages and snacks on two of the levels along with the basement. On the first tier there are lounge areas where you can just relax before or during intermission. The rest room lines are long but move quickly enough so that you can return to your seat in time for the 2nd act.

They also offer some VIP packages where you get special ""perks"" along with better seating for more money. I am taking advantage of one of these perks next year and will update this review to see whether or not my investment was worth it.
Sadly however
column2: they don't always inform you of special name entertainment unless you are a donor. I've missed out on a couple of these attractions for that reason. column1: 770	BacrktTHhhr_LRXCJY_S-w	2015-07-28	3FWTIZkGvckSmCTlXsvukQ	4	"Kennywood park has been a longstanding Pittsburgh tradition of amusement parks. School picnics are held here. Special events including the yearly fall fantasy of bands and parades also are a big draw.

Kennywood park is one of the few remaining amusement parks that offer not only tiered admission but also a ""nightrider"" pass of $26.99 if arriving after 5:00. Discount tickets coupons are also available at local Giant Eagle stores for weekday admission. Senior citizen rates start at age 55.
Kennywood still has picnic tables which has been a longstanding tradition of families bringing food into the park for an event or family gathering.
You are no longer issued wristbands upon entering once you pass the security checkpoint.  Rides are clearly indicated with restrictions and a bar is used to certify height requirements for children.
Kennywood still has their famous iconic rides and eateries
column2: of the latter
column3: the potato patch is the most popular. The train ride has been revamped to give you a pictorial history of the park. The Merry Go Round is the center of its classic elegance and the famous meeting place for friends. Noah's Ark still remains as their trademark walk through dark ride and the famous Thunderbolt
column4: once known as the ""king of the coasters"" provides a thrill seeking ride for those who love wooden coasters. Also among ""hidden"" icons is the famous ""Old Mill"" boat ride which has been remodeled to Garfield's nightmare.

column1: Kennywood offers something for everyone in your family. For thrill seekers
column2: coasters such as ""the Phantom's revenge"" along with Racer and Jack Rabbit offer fun and excitement. There are other thrill rides my personal favorite being the Black widow which is a pendulum style ride where about 50 people sit in a rotating circle as it sways back and forth to extremely high levels!

column1: Kennywood does offer a VIP pass if you wish to purchase it to avoid the lines for coasters only. During weekdays the lines for these rides are not as bad so you can plan your day accordingly.

They have an area called ""Lost Kennywood"" to reflect an era from our grandparent's generation. The park was founded in 1898. Kiddieland is available to small children wanting to ride a miniature version of some of the big named rides. You can see some of it from the train ride.
Water rides like the ""Pittsburgh plunge"" cool you off on an excessive hot day but I see they have now installed pay for drying stations if you don't want to walk around totally soaked.
They are in the process of opening a 4D theater within the week called ""the Ice age"".  All I could see was that it does require 3D glasses.
Food
column2: ice cream
column3: and treats are everywhere. There are two indoor restaurants-the Parkside cafeteria and Johnny Rockets (will be reviewed separately). Handicapped access is also available at most of the rides as well as lockers. Please note you can ""stow"" your gear before boarding certain rides but you do so at your own risk..

column1: They also have daily shows along with plenty of park benches to rest. If you look around you can find more of Kennywood's history such as the historic windmill. Landmark signs point them out. More information about the park can be found on their website.

Finally they will offer rain checks in the event of inclement weather under certain guidelines. Kennywood is a timeless tradition for Pittsburgh and I hope to visit again."	review	9HCfCmd0t5GErgm7He6AeQ	{u'funny': 1
column2: u'useful': 2
column3: u'cool': 2}	3.57	{u'profile': 1

column1: 780	JDDeaNfb0JXD1NbznSIC9g	2009-11-30	oYANxEF4XEvP_1BnkGjFcQ	2	"REDO!
I went to PF Chang's several years ago and was NOT pleased with the food that was presented to me.
My issue: I thought I was getting Chinese food.
My resolution: Try this restaurant again knowing that it is just reinvented American food with names of those Chinese dishes I actually like to eat.

So we returned to PF Chang's for lunch to try this American food in this caricature of a Chinese restaurant.  There were very few people in the restaurant.  The two of us were seated in the largest corner booth and left to review our menus.  When our waitress finally arrived we ordered the following items:
Coca Cola
Iced Tea
Pan fried pork dumplings
Sesame chicken lunch with white rice and egg drop soup
Changs chicken with white rice

Our drinks and my soup came out immediately.  Unfortunately I was brought the wrong soup and the server had disappeared before I had a chance to say anything.  I could see her across the barren wasteland that was the dining room and we even made eye contact several times
column2: but at no point could I get her to come back to my table.  I tried the soup and was disgusted with it and placed it at the end of the table.  I didn't know what it was and didn't want to know.  Almost ten minutes later she arrived quite happy with the job she was doing and asked how the food was.  I asked if she could bring out some egg drop soup. I didn't expect to get the stink-eye.

column1: My egg drop soup was brought out with the dumplings as well as the caddy of different sauces and oils.  The server really wasn't that into the experience
column2: but again gave me the stink-eye when I told her that mixing the sauces was unnecessary since I knew what each of them was and would be able to mix them myself.  I mixed the rice vinegar
column3: chili oil
column5: and soy sauce (my guess is that it was supposed to be tamari) to create a dipping sauce for our dumplings. I took a bite of the soup and it was somewhat better than the other soup
column6: but it was still brown.  I ate half the bowl and left the rest for the server.  It was thick and gooey and the flavor didn't wow.  I saw no reason to continue.  I moved on to the dumplings
column7: which had an okay flavor to them.  The skins were a bit thick and doughy.  The meat on the inside did not balance this attribute at all.  The sauce tasted a little odd so I tried to remix and it was still off.  I tried the components individually and found that some of them were either old
column9: or rancid.  We finished our dumplings.

column1: Our lunch entrees arrived.  I had ordered mine extra-spicy
column2: but I guess it came Pittsburgh Hot (super mild) and had a lackluster flavor at best.  The meat was tough and the sauce tasted of soy sauce more than anything else.  I tried some of Chang's chicken and was equally mollified.  This was supposed to be their version of General Tso's Chicken.  Now I have never had a General's chicken that was the same at any place.  It is always different.  Many of them are good in different ways.  This food
column3: though
column4: it wasn't good.  Chang's chicken fell into the same category as the Sesame Chicken -- since it tasted mainly of soy sauce -- with the addition sugar.

column1: I just don't understand how anyone can like this place.  Even the Yoshida Sauce you get at Sam's/Costco tastes better."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 3
column2: u'useful': 2

column1: It is a very small waiting room and you really don't want to have to wait due to the different animals that are continually coming through the door -- that is vet common sense -- so make certain you call ahead to get an appointment. column2: I let it slide knowing why she was saying it -- positive reinforcement for the puppies is the only way to go people
column3: believe it.  The doctor came in soon after and did the full exam on Sophie.  He was quick and methodical
column4: but at no time did I hear my pup whine.  He pointed out things that he saw and gave Sophie her preliminary vaccinations.

column1: And then all was done.  At no point did he try to up-sell me.  At no point did he or his associates try to give me anything that was not needed.  He was straightforward and plain in his language and he answered all of my questions truthfully.  How do I know?  I already knew the answers to my questions.  I am fairly protective of my Boston Terriers; and as a small breed they have some health idiosyncracies and nuances that many vets don't know about.  He knew the answers.   I was happy.

column2: wings
column3: and bread came out rather quickly.  The garlic bread was nothing special
column4: just a loaf brushed with a garlic oil and warmed.  Very simple

column2: overall

column1: I must say

column5: 1950's ambiance and made our way to one of the booths on the side metal wall.  It did take a bit for our waitress to finally notice us
column6: but she brought the menus as soon as she stopped talking to the other servers and cooks in the rear.  We ordered our cokes and as she left to get the drinks we looked over the menus
column7: intent on having our order ready by the time she came back with our drinks.  When she arrived we placed our order for the following:

column1: Italian Wedding Soup
Hot roast beef with fries
Buffalo Chicken strips {hot}
Large gyro with no lettuce and sauce on the side.

The last two items were both entrees and I ordered both for myself since I figured one of them would be good and one of them might not be so good.  I love both gyros and buffalo chicken strips and I tend to be very forgiving of issues in their preparation because of how much I love them.
The service so far had been very slow.  The arrival of the soup did nothing to reverse my thought on this issue.  The Italian Wedding Soup was not the worst I had ever tried
column2: but it definitely wasn't the best.  It lacked flavor that you expect in an Italian Wedding -- one could get the same flavor from a packet of chicken broth.  My chicken strips arrived to the table and I immediately went for them.

column1: The strips smelled good and looked good -- not too wet
column2: not too dry.  I tried some of the blue cheese -- not so good
column3: I would stay away from this dressing.  I took a bit of a chicken strip and it wasn't bad; it was made from dry
column4: white meat and it wasn't hot.  Maybe Pittsburgh hot
column5: but it was between mild and medium (closer to mild) at best for the rest for me -- remember
column6: it takes a serrano pepper for me to feel a tingle. I wasn't displeased with the strips
column7: but I had definitely had better.

column1: The gyro and the hot roast beef sandwich arrived.  I was happy to have what appeared to be some good looking food.  The issue is that all of the food had looked good so far
column2: while the actual flavor had been underwhelming.  As is my norm
column3: I tried the separate parts first to see what kind of flavor each had.  Trying the gyro sauce
column4: I can honestly say that it wasn't traditional.  The sauce was just ranch.  I really don't care for ranch.  I tried some of the meat and the pita; the meat was under-seasoned and the pita was hard on the outside and chewy on the inside (not good chewy

column1: I moved on to the open-faced roast beef sandwich.  It didn't taste bad
column2: but like the wedding soup it also didn't taste good.  I went back to my gyro and finished it with ranch strategically placed.  Throughout the entire ordeal of tasting the food
column3: my cup went dry.  And it stayed dry -- for a long time.  I eventually had to ask one of the other servers in the restaurant since my server was ignoring my flailing arms in the rear of the restaurant.

column1: As bad as the gyro was
column2: I can honestly say it wasn't the worst that I had ever tried -- Stoupsy's in Miami holds that special place in my heart.  Overall it was a lackluster experience that I really don't want to repeat.  I might return if someone really wants to go.  If I do go back

column1: 818	sI9BnInlCDUos3kYx9StSQ	2009-12-10	2_cXBEUuGV4LqujVq9EJPw	3	"Come for the breakfast ... only get the breakfast.  I came for the breakfast.  I was in the area about three years ago and many of the smaller Mom and Pop diners that I actually liked had closed.  Thankfully this place was still open and I was hungry.  Located near the top of Mount Washington
column2: this little diner benefits by its proximity to the Mount Washington Parking garage.

column1: Rather stark inside
column2: the locals and owners like to dress up the interior and exterior for the holidays.  While we were looked at suspiciously at first
column3: we were accepted into the fold when we placed our order:

column1: Chicken and rice soup
Ham and cheese with homefries
Big Country Breakfast: eggs (poached medium)
column2: bacon (soft)
column3: and blueberry pancakes with toast and homefries

column1: The chicken and rice soup had very little chicken and A LOT of vegetables and the broth was rather flavorless.  I would like to take this time to rename it to Vegetable and Rice soup -- now if only it had some flavor.  As we muddled through the soup
column2: our entrees came to the table.  Did I mention I was hungry?  The Big Country Breakfast looked great.

column1: I went straight for the blueberry pancakes and enjoyed their flavor.  They were good and fluffy and the blueberries had good flavor that just popped in my mouth.  After eating about a quarter of them I moved on to the  eggs.  They were cooked perfectly -- egg whites fully solid and the yolk slightly viscous in the center.  I love eggs when they are cooked perfectly like this since a majority of the yolk will adhere to the whites and then I can come in with my toast and mop up the rest.  OH SO GOOD! And back to the pancakes....then the eggs...and then the bacon.  They listened to me and brought out my bacon soft.  I swear that I am the only person in the world that dislikes crunchy bacon.
I looked over at the omelet but decided not to try it.  It had been browned.  I know it is a psychological thing
column2: but if my eggs are browned I will not touch them.  I will accept my friends comments that it was good.  He finished it and appeared to enjoy it.  The only other down point about the meal were the homefries -- not a lot of flavor to them at all.  I decided to just leave them at the side and eat the rest of my meal.

column1: I enjoyed this experience and will return from time to time.  Even though there is the garage
column2: it can be hectic to find a parking space.  I think that the only reason I would choose this diner over O'Leary's is the pancakes.  They were so much better.  That is fine
column3: though
column4: I go to O'Leary's for the French Toast."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 1

column1: 819	9oImwXLAn-DFppBrfbmkLg	2009-12-06	to_8uxgfz9IBMyeLkr2Faw	4	"Located in Duquesne Heights
column2: you must visit this restaurant.  If for nothing else
column3: just the night time view of downtown Pittsburgh.  It was wonderful.  There is an upper and a lower level to this restaurant.  The upper-level is fairly pretentious and filled with lots of glitz and suits.  The lower-level is where the bar is located and it contains a small amount of window seating.  Many people go to sit upstairs.  Why?  I don't know.  It is so bright and contrived and you cannot get a very good view.  I prefer the darker lower level where people are more down to earth and real and the fact that you can actually see the city lit up at night. Don't let the coat check fool you.  If you feel uncomfortable
column4: just head to the lower level.

column1: We were greeted by our server and handed the menus.  We were able to look through and asked our server for her suggestions.  We placed our order for the recommended  appetizer that was not on the menu:
Combo Platter: Ichiban (tuna
column2: salmon
column3: and swordfish grilled on a skewer)

column1: I was continually distracted by the view.  You can see the Duquesne Incline
column2: the Southside
column3: Downtown and the Northside and it is amazing how the night coupled with lit buildings can create such a sublime and dramatic image on the horizon -- Beautiful.   I had to focus
column5: and was ready for our server when she returned with the appetizer:

column1: French onion soup
Butternut squash soup
Mahi mahi with garlic- feta mashed potatoes
Yellow fin tuna with
column2: garlic-feta mashed potatoes
column3: and tomatoes with balsamic vinaigrette

column1: The tri-partite appetizer combined three of the more popular appetizers on the written menu.  I was quite glad they had this option tonight since I would have been very disappointed to have ordered the Ichiban and the Cajun shrimp as their own dish.  Both were not great and were lacking in flavor.  The fish cubes on the Ichiban skewer were somewhat tough and overcooked with very little flavor.  The shrimp were slightly rubbery and did not taste Cajun.  The price of this appetizer was only $1 more than the crab cake appetizer.  The crab cake was quite good.  It is the best crab cake I have had in the Pittsburgh area.  It was well cooked
column2: moist
column3: tasted of lump crab and had minimal filler.

column1: As we were finishing the appetizer the soups and tomatoes appeared.  My butternut squash soup came in a two-part series to preserve the scant heat in the soup itself and to protect the crab that came at the bottom of my bowl.  The soup was poured over the seeds and crab at the table.  It tasted very good
column2: but unfortunately it cooled rather quickly -- this is on of the issues with Creme Fraiche
column3: you cannot over heat or it will curdle.  I thoroughly enjoyed the flavor of the squash in the smooth soup coupled with the fresh crab
column5: and creme fraiche.  The French Onion soup had a good flavor. Not over-seasoned
column7: and a good consomme as its base.

column1: Our dinners arrived and I was surprised by the size.  The portions were quite large for both entrees and one could have easily been split between two people.  A bit apprehensive after the Ichiban
column2: I tried the tuna to find that the flavor was much better for the entree.  The same held true for the mahi-mahi.  The tuna was cooked to a nice medium rare
column3: had good texture and flavor and was not filled with gristle.  The mahi-mahi was tender
column5: and flavorful.  The blackening seasoning had a good flavor and was mildly piquant.

column1: I moved on to the mashed potatoes and my tomatoes.  There was just a hint of the feta and garlic in the potatoes that complimented the potatoes very well.  The tomatoes were good and the vinaigrette was also tasty.  I do wish that they would have used a better oil and vinegar
column2: though.  The oil was a cheaper brand without much flavor and the balsamic was fairly weak
column3: but with good flavor.

column1: Unable to finish our meals
column2: we decided that we wouldn't bother with desserts.  Next time -- and there will be a next time -- the appetizer will be crab cake only and we will be splitting a meal.  With more than enough food for two
column3: this will also cut the bill considerably.  I will continue to sit on the lower level and I hope that I get our server again."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 1

column1: 820	63M2e_wSmQ8GbLDUau5K6Q	2011-07-10	K06OhFCp9zBiCuRITJsRfg	2	"So many great reviews
column2: so many wonderful comments I have read about this restaurant.  My neighbor personally recommended trying out La Tavola
column3: and so I did.  As with the rest of Mt Washington
column4: parking will either be a pain in the butt or valet.  I arrived at 9:00pm on a Friday night and was lucky enough to find close street parking.

column1: They appeared to have been fairly busy earlier in the day and night
column2: but when I entered about half the tables were empty.  The interior was rather non-descript and I recognized the wall ornamentation from Ross and Marshalls.  We waited for about five minutes before we were seated.  This didn't bother me since all of the servers I saw were moving quick and making rounds to all of their tables and helping each other clean-up.  I was more worried that I would be sat at a table in a corner and lost in that shuffle.  Miraculously
column3: we were sat a two-top in the middle of the entire main dining area.

column1: All of the servers were hustling and bustling and doing what they do and I saw people smiling and laughing with the exception of one that was just talking to one of his tables.  After 15 minutes of waiting and not seeing anyone
column2: I did start to get a tad irritated.  I wondered if the only server that was talking with one of his tables rather than serving or helping the other servers was our server.  I started to stare in his direction and he looked at me a couple of times before something in his head clicked.  He came over and asked if we had been served and I told him no.  He left
column3: returned in a few minutes and apologized.  He was our server.  As we had been waiting for 20 minutes
column4: we new EVERYTHING that we wanted and ordered:

column1: Pepsi
Tea with Lemon
Meatballs as an appetizer
Wedding Soup (in place of salad)
Veal Piccata (no mushrooms) with a side of potatoes
Veal Parmagiana with linguine and red sauce
Our server seemed perturbed that we already knew what we wanted and didn't want to listen to the specials.  Not only did he have a poor attitude from his first contact
column2: but he didn't write anything down.  I didn't order any additional appetizers due to those two facts.  Our server promptly disappeared and we didn't see him for another ten minutes.  I saw every other server in the place several times.  Some of them even stopped to help us and bring bread -- they were all very nice people.  We finally received our drinks -- a Pepsi for my friend and I.  I asked the server if I could have the tea I ordered. He apologized and said he didn't know how he could have forgotten since he had commented earlier on how the kitchen had just brewed a fresh batch.

column1: And then the waiting started anew.  Our server didn't visit our table again for the next thirty minutes.  He would disappear.  He would stop and chat with other tables.  He would stand around and look as all of the other servers were running around
column2: serving
column3: and also helping to clean our server's tables.  He never helped with anyone else.  Thankfully the other servers refilled our drinks and brought bread to us.  We even managed to get the wedding soup from one of the other servers.  It was good.  It had more of a spinach flavor than many other Wedding soups I have eaten

column1: Our food finally arrived.  The serving sizes were a wonderful size.  I was really not liking our server; but that was fine since I had been craving a good piccata for some time.  I wasn't even perturbed by the fact that I had broccoli instead of the potatoes the server stated came with my meal.  As I dug in
column2: I was left in dismay.  The piccata didn't taste of lemon
column3: capers
column4: or wine in any way.  It tasted like a heavy
column5: flour gravy.  To top it off my food wasn't hot

column1: I tried some of my friends veal parmagiana.  I then went to try some of his linguine to find that it was spaghetti.  I didn't hate it
column2: but the red sauce had a weird aftertaste akin to the metallic aftertaste I get from artificial sweeteners.  I finished my food.

column1: I saw several dessert trays being sent to a larger party in the room next door
column2: and the desserts looked good.  I was by no means full and could have eaten more; but I just didn't want to have to deal with this server anymore.  I can't help but wonder if Rachel C. had the same server I had.

column1: So why I haven't I given 1 star?  A 1 star would mean that I would most likely never return
column2: my friend didn't hate his food and I know that piccata is a difficult dish to make.  I think my experience was greatly colored by one of the worst servers I have ever had.  I will return at some point and make certain to try a different food and to get a different server."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 1
column3: u'useful': 2

column1: 822	1vK7gWQ_b5ehAyOidOsYtg	2013-08-18	qgjNPwxI5NeHTCDtLV-xTQ	1	"Let me start by saying that I don't like an over abundance of seasonings in my food. There must always be a balance between base and spice and the smaller the number of base ingredients

column1: Upon entering Aiello's

column3: white

column5: wooden interiors of Mineo's. I put in our dinner order at the counter:

Small Pizza With Pepperoni

column3: much to my chagrin

column5: but they had put a lot of extra Italian seasoning on the inside.

column1: I don't know how people can eat this much Italian spice. I can only assume that the people that like this spicing of their food also like to eat spoonfuls of Italian seasoning out of the spice jar in the cupboard. If not for the Italian Wedding soup I would really want to give this parlor a zero star.

column1: 823	52CzJDb4EakSjEQOUys77Q	2013-07-28	VnfOKQ2wttBTx1nWRzjkAA	3	"""It's nasty. It's so nasty I crave it.""

I was so perplexed by his use of the word ""nasty"" in such a positive manner that I had to try the food. So after watching ""20 Feet from Stardom"" at The Manor Theater
column2: we went to try Mineo's

column1: Like many of the pizza parlors in the area
column2: you must order at the counter. Our order:

column1: Italian Wedding Soup
Meatballs Parmesan
16"" Pepperoni Pizza
It's amazing how many people come in and out of Mineo's
column2: most leaving with only a slice and never taking a seat. I was able to watch the interactions
column3: comings
column4: and goings of the other patrons as I waited in one of the wooden booths. The arrival of he soup was a welcome distraction due to my hunger.

column1: I liked the fact that the soup was not overly complex and that the broth had a strong cheese flavor to it. So many places like to add too many extra items to an already busy soup. I was happy that Mineo's version relied on the main ingredients. I returned to people watching after finishing the soup and waited on the rest of the food to arrive.
The pizza and meatballs arrived a short time later. As hot as the pizza was
column2: I decided to try the meatballs first so as not to scorch my mouth too bad. The flavor of the meatballs were okay. They bordered on having too much filler for my taste. The sauce was the same way
column3: it tasted like the balance of spice to base was a but off. I ate half a meatball and left the rest for others.

column1: I looked over at the pizza and took in the pretty image it created in my mind. I didn't see any pepperoni on it
column2: but figured it must be in there somewhere. Taking a piece
column3: I tested the heat and then took a bite.

column1: The cheese is so thick it's like eating a steak!""

That description came back to me at that moment. And it was not undercooked like so many other pizza places that like it pile on cheese. All of the cheese was melted and it was even browned and bubbling on top - big plus! The pepperoni was hidden within the vast sea of cheese. Personally
column2: I prefer my pepperoni to be on top so that it can crisp
column3: but the  pepperoni they used was fairly tasty even hidden from view.

column1: The one detractor from the pizza was the sauce. In my opinion
column2: it was almost over seasoned. The closer I came to the crust
column3: the thicker the sauce
column5: became. I like the Italian spices
column6: but they are easily overdone very much in the same way that cumin is overdone in many Hispanic foods.

column1: I will be eating at Mineo's again
column2: my friends really enjoyed the cheesiness."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 2
column3: u'useful': 3

column1: 826	-23t2qOQWj8Kqp-Ijm1BQA	2009-11-03	kg9ELtT4lu220hdqyabJCg	1	"I do not understand how this place stays in business.  My comment has nothing to do with the location and everything to do with the food and the service.  I like to think that I am fairly open about assessing a new place
column2: but the is not a Chinese restaurant.  The best thing that I can say about the entire experience is that it didn't taste bad -- there was NO flavor in anything .  Wow...really?  I can only think of the Allegory of the Cave when reading previous reviews and then to feel sorry if this is one of the best Chinese restaurants in Pittsburgh.  Really?!?!?

column1: As I was walking here
column2: I saw that their specialty was sichuan/szechuan and hunan styles of cooking.  I thought that was awesome since I prefer szechuan style cooking.  Don't believe what you read though.  The best approximation of the the taste and texture of this food is the cheap Cantonese dishes that I ordered in Hong Kong -- the difference is that I only paid 25 cents for three times as much food.  The food we ordered:

column1: Pan fried pork dumplings
Wonton
Egg drop
Combo fried rice (yeung chow)
Kung Pao chicken
Unsweet Tea
Coke

The service was HORRIBLE.  The server only had THREE tables and she was running around like Foghorn Leghorn after Colonel Sanders chopped off his head in Family Guy.  What made it worse is that the owner/manager was watching the entire time and not interceding to try and make the experience better.  For your benefit
column2: I will list the order of how my order arrived:

column1: 1. Fried Rice (entree) - after 15 minutes of waiting
2. Egg Drop Soup and Wonton Soup (appetizer) - 10 minutes after the fried rice
3. Coke and Iced Tea (drinks) - 5 minutes after the soup.
4. Kung Pao Chicken (entree) - 20 minutes after our drinks arrived.
5. Dumplings (appetizer) - a good 10 minutes after the Kung Pao chicken.
I am not going to bore you with the poor excuses uttered by the waitress
column2: at least she appeared to be trying in the best way she could.  The fact that the manager/owner was just watching the entire situation just pissed me off.  I didn't finish eating anything.  If you enjoy eating coagulated goop in differing levels of solidity
column3: then this is the place for you.  If you don't like Chinese food because it tastes like the food at this place
column4: please try again in a different place -- this is NOT good Chinese food.

column1: The most amazing part was the table of 5 Chinese men that were sitting at the table next to me.  They were continually asking for items that they were not recieving.  Two of the gentlemen actually went to speak to the manager -- IN CHINESE -- and the manager still did nothing.  Horrendous. At $20 per person
column2: this is quite overpriced.

column1: I shall never return."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 2

column1: 827	kiXE579k_sP6XCj_XUJc4g	2009-12-05	HXC7jbKLx6J8K76_egaUOw	3	"This place is so hard to find.  I know it is in Station Square; that wasn't the hard part.  The hard part was finding the restaurant once I arrived at Station Square.  I really don't care for the organization of this odd mall
column2: but that is another review.  Located at the North-East corner of the complex on the second floor
column3: Sesame Inn is easily missed.  After having called the people several times on my cell trying to figure out where they were located
column4: I was finally able to get to the stairwell leading to the front entry.

column1: Unintelligible Chinese people? Check
Chinese kitsch? Check
Good Chinese Food? Read on...
So far
column2: so good.  Everything was appearing in place and had the proper feeling.  I was craving some good Sichuan food.  We were seated by the host and I looked at the menu solely to make certain that what I wanted to order was present.  When the server arrived I asked her some quick questions to make certain that there wasn't too much of a deviation from what I was craving and ordered:

column1: Egg drop soup
Wonton soup
Panfried pork dumplings
Combination rice (no peas or carrots)
Kung pao
column2: extra spicy
column3: with only peanuts and red bell peppers

column1: Our server was quite peppy and sounded like she was a first generation American since she spoke English flawlessly to us and then spoke Chinese to people in the back.  She was quick to bring out our Iced tea
column2: Pepsi
column3: and soups.  I was a tad taken aback by the appearance of my egg drop soup -- it was a deep red instead of a light yellow.  I spooned it through to make certain it was the right soup and found the cause for the deviation -- the addition of tomatoes to the soup.  Feeling comfortable
column4: I tried the soup.  It wasn't bad
column5: but it wasn't great.  It was thick and heavy with very little of that flowered egg/broth combination that makes for a very good egg drop soup.  I could live with a thicker soup
column6: just don't take away the flavor.  The wonton soup also had that heavier feeling about it as compared to some of the lighter wonton soups that I have tried and enjoyed.

column1: Our panfried dumplings arrived to our table and they smelled good.  While the skins were a little thicker
column2: they weren't dumpling thick and the meat filling helped to balance it in terms of consistency.  The flavor was a bit muted
column3: though.  Trying the dipping sauce
column4: I received a bit of a shock.  Contrary to everything else thus far
column5: it was quite vibrant. The dumpling sauce had a very strong acidic flavor to it and could possibly have use a tad less vinegar in the preparation.  Together
column7: I enjoyed the dumplings and dipping sauce.  And
column9: I would rather the sauce be a little strong on the acid than a little week since I can always dilute with some soy sauce.

column1: Our entrees arrived and they smelled quite good; but I had to send the chicken back.  There were mushrooms.  Sorry
column2: can't eat mushrooms.  While waiting on the chicken to return
column3: we started on the fried rice.  It wasn't bad
column4: but it wasn't great.  It was fully cooked
column5: but it was a bit soggy.  The meats were somewhat flavorless and only added another texture to the whole dish.  The flavor of the dish as a whole did not transcend being rice and meat.  A good fried rice really helps me understand the adage
column6: ""Greater than the sum of the parts.""

column1: As we were finishing the fried rice
column2: the new chicken arrived.  It was steaming hot and smelled good.  It looked to be more in a red sauce than a glaze as is customary with Sichuan foods.  I figured as long as it tasted good then there would be no issue.  I took my first bite.  It was sweet.  It wasn't piquant.  I had asked the server if items were spicy.  I had asked her about which peppers she thought were hot.  The chicken tasted okay
column3: but it was nothing spectacular.  I continued to eat the entree and finished it.  It could have at least have been made from white meat since it was not spicy.  Oh well.

column1: They don't serve Sichuan food here.  It is too heavy and sauce oriented.  I would say that it has to be some mixture of Cantonese
column2: Hunan and Mandarin. Will I return
column3: probably not.  Why?  I just don't like the Station Square location.  There are other Sesame Inn in Ross Township and Dormont.  I will most likely try again at one of those related restaurants to see if I like anything else on the menu.  For better or worse
column4: it is one of the better Chinese in the area."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 2

column1: 828	CB8p5dGrqZxc06vs_xDOHw	2009-12-16	LNGrWnVJoWBb4m4kFgMQcw	4	"Something has to be good since this restaurant has been in businees for 25 years.  Our server has worked here for 10 years.  It was quite interesting to see that the servers were quite obviously the children of the owners.  The amazing part was that they were quite professional during the duration of our meal.  Having had some fairly bad Chinese food in the area
column2: I was on my last ounce of hope.

column1: The interior is very sparsely decorated
column2: but it reminded me of the little mom and pop places that I saw in Suzhou
column3: China.  I was intrigued by this little Chinese restaurant in Homestead that was packed with locals.  Since I hadn't satisfied my Chinese craving yet
column4: I already knew what I wanted and told the server the entire order:

column1: Panfried Pierogi/Dumplings
Egg Drop Soup
Wonton Soup
Yeung chow (combo fried rice
column2: no peas
column3: no carrots)

column1: Generals (Piquancy 7/10)
As I ordered
column2: the kids were bringing out food to the other tables and it smelled wonderful.  Our soups arrived rather fast.  I went directly for my egg drop soup and was hit by this taste of white pepper.  Too much white pepper was in the soup.  I tried the wonton soup and it had the same issue -- too much white pepper.  This wasn't a deal-killer since the soups both still had a decent flavor; I just had to get past that white pepper flavor.  The egg drop soup was a bit heavier than I would normally get
column3: but after the ones at Mandarin Gourmet and Sesame Inn

column1: The panfried dumplings arrived to the table.  My eyes and belly were happy to see these dumplings.  They were a little thick
column2: but the meat and the shells were well-flavored and the dipping sauce had a good mixture of sweet
column3: salty
column4: and acidic.  We quickly devoured the dumplings with a swiftness.  I did find it amusing that they were shaped just like pierogies -- was this to help the locals?  I don't know
column5: but they tasted good.  While eating our food
column6: the same dish was being served to table after table on a sizzling skillet and it smelled wonderful.  When the little bus-girl took our plate
column7: I asked her what it was and she said it was the Garlic Chicken -- I am adding that to my list of items to try here.

column1: Our entrees arrived; the General's Chicken -- true to form -- was completely different from every single other Chinese restaurant in the world.  It was the chunk
column2: fried variety with a fairly dark
column3: thick sauce.  It was definitely NOT piquant at a 7 (mental note for a 10 next time) and the flavor was different.  It was slightly salty with a bitter taste that wasn't offensive.  I wish it were a bit more piquant.

column1: The combination fried rice wasn't bad.  It was better than most fried rices
column2: but it used the salad shrimp.  I have become used to eating my yeung chow fried rice with actual shrimp in it.  Other than that little irksome item
column3: I enjoyed my friend rice.  It wasn't drenched in soy sauce even though it was a little oily.

column1: We ate all of the food
column2: and as I was reviewing the check
column3: the old lady behind me placed her order.  She asked for a 10 with a side of chili sauce.  I was surprised but I realized that my instincts were correct about ordering a 10/10 next time.

column1: This is a 3.5 stars
column2: but bumped up to 4 since I know I will return."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 2
column3: u'useful': 2

column1: 829	-vVQyTVHitF6TOHGijVXxQ	2009-11-09	QDagEN0p8NCsq_WZAXEhng	3	"I think I was expecting a tad more when I entered these doors.  We were seated promptly and ordered the following items:
Pepsi
Tea

Smokey burger with fries

I was really jonesing to try the Killer wings...I really enjoy food that is piquant with good flavor.  The waitress just looked at me and asked if I was certain and I said yes.  After waiting for a few minutes we recieved the wings and the chicken soup.  The chicken soup was really nothing special.  It was obvious that it was made from fresh ingredients
column2: but the flavors were not in balance -- certain herbs were masking the flavor of the chicken partially while completely smothering the taste of the vegetables.

column1: I put my nose close to the wings and took a good whiff.  I was suprised to find that my nose did not retaliate.  I knew right off the bat that they were not as hot as billed.  I dug into the killer wings and ate two of them before I switched to the original wings.  I was not impressed.  The heat is NOT commensurate with the flavor in either the killer nor the original.  In fact
column2: the flavor of the killer wings was subpar compared to the original wings.  Do not get these wings unless you hang out with a bunch of people that have no affinity for piquant foods and you are trying to show off.  The flavor is just not worth it.  The original wings
column3: while not as bad as the killer
column4: had a bit of a sweet base to them rather than the acidic base that I am so fond of...if you like sweeter things
column5: you may like these.  I will be going for one of the 3/5 fat heads in piquancy next time to see if there is a better equilibrium between heat and flavor.

column1: As I was finishing the last of the wings
column2: our sandwich arrived.  The flavor was somewhat lackluster; there was just too much bread.  As I was eating the hamburger
column3: I started to speak to our server and she asked how the sandwich was.  She stated that for some reason the company they purchase bread from gave them rolls that were larger than normal and she was wondering what we thought.  Being myself
column4: I told her about the overabundance of bread.

column1: While the food itself wasn't that great
column2: I must say that the service was exemplary.  At no point did I feel smothered nor did I feel neglected.  Our servers chipper and up-front attitude definitely earned points in my book.  I will return
column3: if nothing else to have a beer or two; but I do want to retry the burger to see how it is with the proper ratio of bread to burger."	review	T_wjLgPOPXry7Bea4MzoVQ	{u'funny': 2

column1: I had been to Primanti Brothers before

column24: and I think it gave the sausage a nice flavor
column25: and rendered it both crispy and juicy.  I was definitely pleased.
